It's time to finish the holidays preparations. Even if you've got last minute shopping to do, cooking and baking, some meetings still hanging in your calendar, do your best not to skip going to the gym. Here's 4 reasons why:
.
1. Going to the gym will help you disconnect from all the last minute holiday stress.
.
2. It will be a great reminder of all you've accomplished fitness wise this year and that's valuable because you'll be less likely to binge eat over the holidays.
.
3. It will make you feel great. Just envision that moment after a good training session - covered in sweat, down on the floor, but so satisfied you pushed yourself again.
.
4. Make room for all the food. Although we should try our best not overdo anything, temptation is much bigger during the holidays. With another workout in, you'll bounce back faster and surely feel less guilty after that second slice of turkey.
.

Both fish oil and kirll oil contain these two types of omega-3 fatty acids: eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA) and docosahexaenoic acid (DHA). EPA and DHA are known to benefit your heart, brain, liver and joints. But the differences between the two oils are quite big and not easy to neglect.
.
To put it simply, the fatty acids in fish oil are found in the form of triglycerides, whereas the fatty acids in krill oil are mostly found in the form of phospholipids, which have a higher absorption and effectiveness rate.
.
Fish oil has a content of about 30% of EPA and DHA. It has¬†very low antioxidant levels and because of this, it will more likely to oxidate and get rancid. This can release damiging free radicals inside your body.
.
Krill oil has a content of 14% EPA and DHA, but the phospholipid structure of these fatty acid makes krill oil much more absorbable. Krill oil is rich in vitamins A, E and D. It also contains high levels of the antioxidant astaxanthin.¬†Krill oil is 48 times more potent than fish oil. It has over 300 times the antioxidant power of vitamins A and E. Over 47 times the antioxidant power of lutein and over 34 times the antioxidant power of coenzyme Q10.
.
For more info on krill oil vs fish oil, check out the link in bio.
.
